07136nam a22009255i 9783110770216DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20222022gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2021950693  a97831107702167 a10.1515/97831107702162doi  a(DE-B1597)611985  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aPHI034000 2bisacsh04a006.300aArtificial Intelligence and Human Enhancement :bAffirmative and Critical Approaches in the Humanities /ced. by Herta Nagl-Docekal, Waldemar Zacharasiewicz. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (VII, 328 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aWiener Reihe : Themen der Philosophie ,x2363-9237 ;v2100tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction: Affirmative and Critical Approaches to Artificial Intelligence and Human Enhancement -- tPart 1: Challenging “Strong AI” from the Perspective of Human Agency -- tThe Artificiality of the Human Mind: A Reflection on Natural and Artificial Intelligence -- tMerits and Limits of AI: Philosophical Reflections on the Difference between Instrumental Rationality and Praxis-Related Hermeneutical Reason -- tExperience, Identity and Moral Agency in the Age of Artificial Intelligence -- tOutsourcing the Brain, Optimizing the Body: Retrotopian Projections of the Human Subject -- tLife Care/Lebenssorge and the Fourth Industrial Revolution -- tPart 2: Examining Merits and Limits of Applied AI -- tAI’s Winograd Moment; or: How Should We Teach Machines Common Sense? Guidance from Cognitive Science -- tPassing the Turing Test? AI Generated Poetry and Posthuman Creativity -- tWhy Neuroenhancement is a Philosophical Issue -- tThe Future of Artificial Intelligence in International Healthcare: An Index -- tPart 3: Encounters with Artificial Beings in Film, Literature, and Theater -- tDark Ecology and Digital Images of Entropy: A Brief Survey of the History of Cinematic Morphing and the Computer Graphics of Artificial Intelligence -- tSentience, Artificial Intelligence, and Human Enhancement in US-American Fiction and Film: Thinking With and Without Consciousness -- t“I, Robot”: Artificial Intelligence and Fears of the Posthuman -- tAI on Stage: A Cross-Cultural Check-Up and the Case of Canada and John Mighton -- tArtificial Intelligence from Science Fiction to Soul Machines: (Re‐)Configuring Empathy between Bodies, Knowledge, and Power -- tList of contributors -- tIndex of Authors -- tIndex of Subjects0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe technological innovations that have made "learning" computers possible are being met with utopian hopes as well as apocalyptic apprehensions. Will AI research eventually lead to software systems that have consciousness and are capable of autonomous decision making? The essays challenge "strong AI" from the perspective of human agency and moral judgment, explain the categorical difference between vulnerable humans and AI devices, and discuss diverse forms of applied AI, such as prograns of natural language processing, computional creativity, neuroenhancement, and the use of AI in international healthcare. These theoretical issues are illustrated in essays that focus on the encounter with artificial beings in film, literature and theater. Examining science fiction that blurs the borderline between humans and deep-learning androids, the essays explore, and challenge, ways of questioning human exceptionalism, for instance by visualizing non-conscious cognition and sentience. The book suggests a sober distinction between well-argued achievements of digital technology and excessive, unfounded expectations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 4aDigitaler Humanismus. 4aKünstliche Intellig